DSL-3580L (chipnum 0x4352, device 0x43b3) bring-up hits a fatal DMA
error at the first RX descriptor fetch:

  b43-phy1 ERROR: Fatal DMA error: 0x00001000, 0x0, 0x0, 0x0, 0x0, 0x0

(I_DE on dma_reason[0], TX channels clean — the first RX fetch after
b43_mac_enable, before any TX attempt.) Root cause traced to
b43_dma_init() on BCMA + DMA64 emitting transactions toward
0x80000000_<ringbase>, which the BCM63xx PCIe RC does not recognise.

Static audit of wlDSL-3580_EU.o_save (_dma_ddtable_init @0x10678
and dma_attach chip dispatch @0x14860..0x14894) shows the OEM blob
uses (translation_low, translation_high) = (0x40000000, 0) for chip
0x4352 — i.e. DMA32_CMT value in the LOW word, not DMA64_CMT in HIGH.

New directory kernel-patch/dma-4352-translation/ carries the b43
fix in the same DRAFT-style format as sprom-rev11/:
  - 0001-*.patch: two-hunk change to drivers/net/wireless/broadcom/b43/dma.c
    introducing b43_is_bcm4352_family() and gating both
    b43_dma_translation_in_low_word() and the BCMA arm of
    b43_dma_init() on it. No change to shared bus code.
  - README.md: full provenance (decode of the fatal, OEM offsets,
    apply order, verification status, open points).

Cross-reference added to kernel-patch/README.md as a sibling of the
sprom-rev11 blocker entry.
